Campus Recruitment (kaggle)- Academic and Employability Factors influencing placement¶

Argyrios Georgiadis¶

January 2022¶

Introduction¶

The dataset has been taken from https://www.kaggle.com/benroshan/factors-affecting-campus-placement and included the following columns:

sl_no Serial Number
Gender - Male='M',Female='F'
ssc_p Secondary Education percentage- 10th Grade
ssc_b Board of Education- Central/ Others
hsc_p Higher Secondary Education percentage- 12th Grade
hsc_b Board of Education- Central/ Others
hsc_s Specialization in Higher Secondary Education
degree_p Degree Percentage
degree_t Under Graduation(Degree type)- Field of degree education
workex Work Experience
etest_p Employability test percentage ( conducted by college)
specialisation Post Graduation(MBA)- Specialization
mba_p MBA percentage
status Status of placement- Placed/Not placed
salary Salary offered by corporate to candidates

Data Preprocessing¶

In [17]:
#create a copy
students_copy = students.copy()
#drop not needed columns
students_copy=students_copy.drop(columns = ['sl_no','salary'])
#replace binary columns with 1 and 0
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
le = LabelEncoder()
students_copy["gender"] = le.fit_transform(students_copy["gender"])
students_copy["ssc_b"] = le.fit_transform(students_copy["ssc_b"])
students_copy["hsc_b"] = le.fit_transform(students_copy["hsc_b"])
students_copy["workex"] = le.fit_transform(students_copy["workex"])
students_copy["specialisation"] = le.fit_transform(students_copy["specialisation"])
students_copy["status"] = le.fit_transform(students_copy["status"])
#one hot encoding from hsc_s and degree_t
students_copy = pd.get_dummies(students_copy, columns=['hsc_s'], drop_first = True)
students_copy = pd.get_dummies(students_copy, columns=['degree_t'], drop_first = True)

# Create arrays for the features and the response variable
y = students_copy['status'].values
X = students_copy.drop('status', axis=1).values
#import packages from sklearn
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
#split data in train and test
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y,
test_size = 0.3, random_state=42,stratify=y)

Fit data with several models¶

Below, I fit the data with several models, calculate the time it takes the models to run, calculate the f1 score and roc_auc_score for each model, plot for all models for comparison reasons. Finally, in some cases I tuned the models hyperparameters for best fitting

In [20]:
#fit K Neighbors Classifies, find the best k and then f-again
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
param_grid = {'n_neighbors': np.arange(10, 60)}
knc = KNeighborsClassifier()
knc_cv = GridSearchCV(knc, param_grid, cv=5)
knc_cv.fit(X, y)
knc_cv.best_params_

In [21]:
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score
import time
start_time = time.time()
knc = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=12)
knc.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred_knc = knc.predict(X_test)
roc_auc_score_knc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_knc)
f1_score_knc = f1_score(y_test, y_pred_knc)
end_time = time.time()
time_knc = end_time - start_time
print('Test set f1_score of knc: {:.2f}'.format(f1_score_knc))
print('Test set roc_auc_score of knc: {:.2f}'.format(roc_auc_score_knc))
print("Result calculated in {:.5f} sec".format(time_knc))

Test set f1_score of knc: 0.83
Test set roc_auc_score of knc: 0.67
Result calculated in 0.01400 sec

# find the best parameters for Decision Tree Classifier
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
# Define the grid of hyperparameters 'params_dt'
params_dt = {
'max_depth': [2, 5,10],
'max_features': [0.2, 0.4,0.6, 0.8]
}

dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)

grid_dt = GridSearchCV(estimator=dt,
param_grid=params_dt,scoring='accuracy',
cv=5)

# Fit 'grid_dt' to the training data
grid_dt.fit(X_train, y_train)
best_hyperparams = grid_dt.best_params_
print('Best hyerparameters:\n', best_hyperparams)

Best hyerparameters:
 {'max_depth': 5, 'max_features': 0.4}

Best Feature selection using SelectKBest¶

In [32]:
#use selectkbest for find the best features with this method
# I was receiving an error that I can have negative values so I will use the data for finding the best k before scaling

from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest
from sklearn.feature_selection import chi2
#create a copy
students_kbest = students.copy()
#drop not needed columns
students_kbest=students_kbest.drop(columns = ['sl_no','salary'])
#replace binary columns with 1 and 0
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
le = LabelEncoder()
students_kbest["gender"] = le.fit_transform(students_kbest["gender"])
students_kbest["ssc_b"] = le.fit_transform(students_kbest["ssc_b"])
students_kbest["hsc_b"] = le.fit_transform(students_kbest["hsc_b"])
students_kbest["workex"] = le.fit_transform(students_kbest["workex"])
students_kbest["specialisation"] = le.fit_transform(students_kbest["specialisation"])
students_kbest["status"] = le.fit_transform(students_kbest["status"])
#one hot encoding from hsc_s and degree_t
students_kbest = pd.get_dummies(students_kbest, columns=['hsc_s'], drop_first = True)
students_kbest = pd.get_dummies(students_kbest, columns=['degree_t'], drop_first = True)

y_kbest = students_kbest['status'].values
X_kbest = students_kbest.drop('status', axis=1).values

fs = SelectKBest(score_func=chi2, k='all')
z = fs.fit_transform(X_kbest, y_kbest)
In [33]:
# Create a pd.Series of features importances
importances_SKBest = pd.Series(fs.scores_, index = students_kbest.drop('status', axis=1).columns)
# Sort importances_rf
sorted_importances_SKBest = importances_SKBest.sort_values()
# Make a horizontal bar plot
sorted_importances_SKBest.plot(kind='barh', color='lightgreen')
plt.ylabel('Feature')
plt.title('Feature importance using Select K Best')
plt.show();

Based on the feature selection, I will create rf models with 2,3,4,5 and 6 features and see how those models perform and compare them. For comparison reason, I will not tune the models for each but use the best parameters as found in previous stage.

Summary¶

In this project, I explored a university student dataset and how possible it is for them to be placed for work placement. I used several models to predict whether they will be placed or not. Seems like the random forest model performs better, but it is slower. I also explore how models with less features perform.
